def gen_checklist(h1, desc, slug):
    parts = []
    parts.append('<section style="margin-top:32px">')
    parts.append('<h2>How to use this checklist</h2>')
    parts.append('<p>This checklist exists because vehicle handover disputes almost always come down to the same question: what was the condition of the vehicle at the moment of transfer, and what is the condition now? A good checklist forces you to capture the specific evidence that answers that question. A great checklist automates the capture so you cannot skip steps when you are in a hurry.</p>')
    parts.append('<p>The single highest-leverage item on any vehicle handover checklist is a time-stamped, geo-located photo set of the vehicle at the moment of transfer. That is exactly what CarShake produces in 60 seconds — a guided 8-angle walkaround scan with automatic timestamping and geo-location, plus a QR handover receipt the operator scans to acknowledge the condition. Run it before and after the handover and you have a court-admissible before/after diff that wins disputes.</p>')
    parts.append('<h2>The core workflow</h2>')
    parts.append('<ol>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Pre-handover scan (60 seconds):</strong> open CarShake, run the guided 8-angle walkaround. Photos are time-stamped and geo-located automatically.</li>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>QR receipt acknowledgement:</strong> generate the QR handover receipt and have the operator scan it at the moment of transfer.</li>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Post-handover scan (60 seconds):</strong> when you get the car back, run the same guided scan.</li>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Review the diff:</strong> CarShake highlights any new damage between the two scans.</li>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Export if needed:</strong> if new damage is present, export the before/after diff with timestamps and geo-data for the claim, dispute letter, or insurance filing.</li>')
    parts.append('</ol>')
    parts.append('<h2>Why most checklists fail</h2>')
    parts.append('<p>Most vehicle handover checklists fail for one of three reasons: (1) they require manual photo capture that does not include trustworthy timestamps, so the other party can claim the photos were taken at any time; (2) they do not include an operator acknowledgement step, so the other party denies receiving the vehicle in the documented condition; or (3) they are too long and get skipped when the driver is in a hurry. CarShake solves all three by automating the capture, forcing the QR acknowledgement, and keeping the entire workflow under 60 seconds.</p>')
    parts.append('<h2>The economics</h2>')
    parts.append('<p>The average valet damage claim runs $2,100. A single disputed claim costs $500+ in deductibles, time, and stress. Pair this checklist with a CarShake scan and the whole thing takes 60 seconds. The free tier includes 3 scans — enough to prove the workflow on your next handover before paying anything. Founding spots (73 of 100 remain) lock the $2.97/month price forever.</p>')
    parts.append('</section>')
    return "\n".join(parts)


def gen_cost(h1, desc, slug):
    parts = []
    parts.append('<section style="margin-top:32px">')
    parts.append('<h2>What vehicle damage actually costs</h2>')
    parts.append('<p>The real cost of a damage dispute is almost never just the repair bill. Drivers focus on the sticker price of the dent repair and miss the cascade of costs that follow: the deductible on your insurance claim, the time off work to get multiple estimates, the hours on the phone with the valet company\'s insurance, the rental car while yours is in the shop, the diminished-value hit when you eventually sell or trade in the car, and the stress tax of fighting a denial for weeks. Add it all up and the average valet damage claim runs roughly $2,100 — and a single disputed claim, even one you ultimately win, costs $500+ out of pocket.</p>')
    parts.append('<h2>The cost breakdown</h2>')
    parts.append('<ul>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Repair cost:</strong> the actual body work. Bumper corner damage from a valet typically runs $400-$900. Wheel curb rash runs $150-$400 per wheel. Door dings $75-$250.</li>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Insurance deductible:</strong> typically $250-$1,000, paid out of pocket before coverage kicks in.</li>')
    parts.append('<strong>Diminished value:</strong> a car with a damage history on its Carfax sells for less. Even after a perfect repair, a late-model car can lose $1,000-$3,000 in resale value.</li>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Time cost:</strong> getting three estimates, filing the claim, fighting the denial, renting a replacement car. Realistically 8-20 hours of your time.</li>')
    parts.append('<li><strong>Stress and hassle:</strong> unquantifiable but real. Most drivers give up on legitimate claims because the fight is not worth it.</li>')
    parts.append('</ul>')
    parts.append('<h2>The 60-second fix</h2>')
    parts.append('<p>The entire cost cascade above is preventable with a single habit: run a time-stamped, geo-located scan of your car before and after anyone else takes possession of it. CarShake was built to make this habit take 60 seconds instead of 10 minutes. The workflow is always the same: open the app, run the guided 8-angle scan, generate the QR handover receipt for the operator to acknowledge, run the same scan when you get the car back, review the before/after diff. If new damage shows up, you have a court-admissible record showing exactly when and where it appeared.</p>')
    parts.append('<p>Operators who would otherwise stonewall you for weeks tend to resolve claims in a single conversation when confronted with a time-stamped, acknowledged before/after diff. The documentation changes the power dynamic. You are no longer making an allegation; you are presenting evidence.</p>')
    parts.append('<h2>The economics</h2>')
    parts.append('<p>The CarShake free tier includes 3 full scans — enough to document a complete round-trip handover and prove the workflow fits your life before paying anything. The Founding tier is $2.97/month, locked forever for founding members (73 of 100 spots remain). At that price, one prevented dispute pays for roughly 14 years of CarShake. There is no scenario in which a driver who hands their keys to anyone else even a few times a year does not come out far ahead.</p>')
    parts.append('</section>')
    return "\n".join(parts)


